{{Distinguish|William H. Macy}}
{{BLP IMDb refimprove|date=July 2010}}
'''Bill Macy''' (born '''Wolf Martin Garber'''; May 18, 1922) is an [[United States|American]] television, film and stage actor, born in [[Revere, Massachusetts]], to Mollie (n√©e Friedopfer) and Michael Garber, a manufacturer.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/93/Bill-Macy.html Bill Macy profile at FilmReference.com]</ref> 

Macy is best known for playing Walter Findlay, the long-suffering husband of the title character on the 1970s [[television]] [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]''. He was also an original cast member of the long-running theatrical revue ''[[Oh! Calcutta!]]'' He has made more than 70 appearances on film and television, including a memorable role as the co-inventor of the 'Opti-grab' in the 1979 [[Steve Martin]] comedy ''[[The Jerk]]'', and as the head television writer in ''[[My Favorite Year]]'' (1982).

He appeared in the popular television movie 'Perry Mason & The Case Of The Murdered Madame'(1987) as banker Richard Wilson. Richard Wilson, along with three other bankers, employed the murder victims public relation company, prior to murder. 

He appeared occasionally on ''[[Seinfeld]]'' as one of the residents of the Florida retirement community in which [[Jerry Seinfeld]]'s parents lived. He also appeared on the short-lived sitcom ''[[Back to You]]''.<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0534409/ IMDb profile]</ref> He made a guest appearance as a patient on [[Chicago Hope]] and an aging gambler on the series ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]''. In 2006 he made an appearance on ''[[My Name is Earl]]'' in the second season episode, "[[Van Hickey]]", as an elderly patient in a nursing home who claims he "once tongue-kissed a Jamaican woman".

